pdTO1eHINa4.description:
I'm saddened and frustrated by how I often I come across the "my 8 year old is an attacking mid, my 9 year old is a keeper, my 7 year old is a striker..." stuff.

99.9% of "Elite" youth players in America can't control the ball at their feet or check their shoulder! An 11 year old is NOT a position!

Please don't worry so much about what position your young player plays (when they are young they should play them all anyway). They need to become soccer players, not strikers, or wingers or attacking midfielders.

Here are six simple ball control V-style patterns you must practice.  These drills are a great way to get comfortable using all parts of your feet when controlling the ball.

uzX-0-Dt2o4.title: Ball Mastery Toe Touches Soccer Skills Challenge
uzX-0-Dt2o4.description:
One of the most underrated ball mastery moves is the simple toe touch or toe tap.  It's one of the first "moves" taught and is usually used as a warm up for other moves.

Now, I don't think there is anything wrong with using simple toe touches first in a ball mastery session.  However, I believe toe touches are much more important than just as a warm up.

They seem really simple so not a lot is put into them.  But just like juggling, toe touches are really important in developing a player's touch.  In order to keep the ball still while doing the most basic toe touches while standing still, you need a soft touch. 

Many times you'll see the ball move too much because the touch is heavy, or the player isn't even touching the ball at all.

And that doesn't even include toe touch skills that involve moving the ball.

Don't just do toe touches.  Master them.

Here's a soccer skills session with six different moves based around toe touches.  There are many, many more.  Many players will think they are too advanced for toe touches.  I don't believe that's ever true.

Give it a shot.  How about 300, 400, 500 or more touches per move?  Or take a time, such as 15 or 20 minutes and see how many touches you can get?  Switch moves every minute.  Rest when you need to.

Toe Touches
Double Scissors / Toe Touches
Brazilian Toe Touches
Side to Side Toe Touches
Bells / Toe Touches
Toe Touches Forward / Backward

VQkURHwZiTE.title: Ball Mastery Drills - Lateral Training Foot Skills With Bells
VQkURHwZiTE.description:
Here's a six pattern ball mastery training session.  
Do this session every day for the next four days.

Day 1 Beginner 100 touches per pattern (600 total) Elite 200 touches (1200 total)
Day 2 Beginner 150 touches per pattern (900 total) Elite 300 touches per pattern (1800 total)
Day 3 Beginner 200 touches per pattern (1200 total) Elite 400 touches per pattern (2400 total)
Day 4 Beginner 250 touches per pattern (1500 total) Elite 500 touches per pattern (3000 total)

Tip;  As the touches increase, do rounds instead of doing them all at once.  For example, on day 2 for beginner you can do each pattern for 100 touches and then go through them again for 50 touches each.  For day 2 of elite, you can do 2 rounds of 150 touches or 3 rounds of 100 touches each.

Remember, practice the pattern so you know it without having to think about it.  If you have to stop and think, you'll prevent yourself from increasing your speed.

Get it right first.  Don't rush speed.  As you get it right, you can increase your speed.  When you start messing up a lot, slow it back down.  Over time (not one session), you'll do it correctly at a faster speed.

The reason we do this is muscle memory.  If you try and go faster than you can your body is going to learn to do it incorrectly.  But if you never challenge yourself to get faster, you'll never get faster.  It's a balance.
